                <div type="general">
                    <p xml:space="preserve">Sidi Bel Abbès is a large city in northwest Algeria south of Oran. It is named after its patron saint, Sīdī bi-l-ˁAbbās, who is buried there. The city developed from a French camp established in 1843.</p>
                    <p xml:space="preserve">The geographical situation of Sidi Bel Abbès makes it not only an economic, social, and cultural melting pot, but also a linguistic hub. Its dialect is considered to be the extreme easternmost of the Bedouin dialects spoken in western Morocco.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div type="researchHistory">
                    <p xml:space="preserve">Research on the dialect of Sidi Bel Abbès began rather late. <rs type="bibl" ref="zotID:ZIBEZC3Q">Madouni 
               (1993)</rs> is an analysis of the discourse particle <hi rendition="#i">ṛā</hi>, and <rs type="bibl" ref="zotID:V3WRYSFF">Madouni 
               (1995)</rs> discusses verbal auxiliaries. Two articles of the same author deal with verbal morphology: <rs type="bibl" ref="zotID:3T4JKAFK">Madouni 
               (2000)</rs> is a short essay on Form V verbs; and <rs type="bibl" ref="zotID:4QXN4SFP">Madouni (2000-2001)</rs> treats 
               the quadriliteral verbs of this dialect.</p>
                    
                    <p xml:space="preserve"><rs type="bibl" ref="zotID:JHKXJ5B2">Raoud (2016)</rs> is a sociolinguistic study on dialectal 
               variation and the direction of linguistic change. The author examines phonological, morphological, and lexical 
               variation based mainly on age, but also on factors like education, sex, and rural/urban origin.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div type="dictionaries">
                    <p xml:space="preserve"><rs type="bibl" ref="zotID:U44AJ8AT">Madouni (2003)</rs> also includes the region of Sidi Bel Abbès.</p>
                </div>
                
